to be able to easily find those settings.

70
00:03:58,144 --> 00:04:01,808
So I've already mentioned in-game communication quite a few times.

71
00:04:02,229 --> 00:04:06,013
Also, it's in the presentation title, so you're probably wondering what I mean by that.

72
00:04:08,015 --> 00:04:12,200
The goal here is to allow players to communicate with one another in an accessible way.

73
00:04:12,880 --> 00:04:18,527
This can include voice chat, text chat, canned chat, contextual chat, emotes, and more.

74
00:04:19,419 --> 00:04:23,521
Navigation is also important because, again, if you can't get to these settings and use them,

75
00:04:24,161 --> 00:04:30,303
they're not very helpful. So menu narration is one way of handling navigation for people who

76
00:04:30,363 --> 00:04:35,085
have different types of vision issues. But before I get into any more details, since this will come

77
00:04:35,185 --> 00:04:43,868
up and there's always a good time to discuss it, legible font. Legible font is one of the biggest

78
00:04:43,968 --> 00:04:47,310
issues we have for accessibility in the game industry at this time.

79
00:04:48,657 --> 00:04:51,358
I recommend a minimum of 28 pixel tall,

80
00:04:51,778 --> 00:04:53,899
3 pixel wide font on a 1080p screen,

81
00:04:53,979 --> 00:04:56,080
and that comes from a variety of user research.

82
00:04:56,800 --> 00:04:58,341
That may seem rather big,

83
00:04:58,741 --> 00:05:00,882
but if you're talking about the television industry,

84
00:05:01,342 --> 00:05:03,943
their minimum font size recommendations on things like

85
00:05:03,983 --> 00:05:09,385
captioning is actually 80 pixels tall in this scenario.

86
00:05:09,425 --> 00:05:12,247
28 pixels really isn't very big.

87
00:05:12,427 --> 00:05:14,968
We recommend a 4.5 to 1 contrast ratio or better.

88
00:05:15,784 --> 00:05:19,408
I actually have a slide at the very end that links to a tool to find this out.

89
00:05:19,749 --> 00:05:23,774
But basically this means you have to have enough contrast between your text and your

90
00:05:23,814 --> 00:05:27,979
background so it stands out enough so people have the best chance of being able to see

91
00:05:28,019 --> 00:05:28,080
it.

92
00:05:28,841 --> 00:05:29,601
So keep that in mind.

93
00:05:30,251 --> 00:05:35,093
Also recommend for all types of venues, including those relating to game communication,

94
00:05:35,653 --> 00:05:41,595
use sans-serif fonts, so things without a lot of flourishes. Examples could be Arial, Helvetica,

95
00:05:41,655 --> 00:05:46,216
Verdana, and Comic Sans. This presentation is actually in Verdana, and I can guarantee you

96
00:05:46,256 --> 00:05:50,818
that everything on this presentation is 4.5 to 1 contrast or better. I highly recommend

97
00:05:51,898 --> 00:05:52,818
using these types of fonts.

98
00:05:53,333 --> 00:05:56,595
Comic Sans tends to get a bad reputation, but really,

99
00:05:56,615 --> 00:05:59,938
it's a very, very good font, particularly for dyslexia.

100
00:06:01,099 --> 00:06:03,140
Those with dyslexia have trouble distinguishing different

101
00:06:03,160 --> 00:06:06,082
characters, and the way Comic Sans is made makes it very easy

102
00:06:06,123 --> 00:06:09,585
for them to use, more so than most actual fonts made

103
00:06:09,605 --> 00:06:10,246
for dyslexia.

104
00:06:11,146 --> 00:06:12,327
So, I highly recommend that.

105
00:06:12,547 --> 00:06:14,969
Keep in mind that font is so important in so many places

106
00:06:15,009 --> 00:06:17,691
that like the defense industry, a lot of places insist

107
00:06:17,731 --> 00:06:20,653
on using that font for all business documents simply

108
00:06:21,034 --> 00:06:22,135
because it's easy to read.

109
00:06:23,036 --> 00:06:23,937
So keep that in mind.

110
00:06:24,357 --> 00:06:27,700
It is okay to have alternate fonts.

111
00:06:27,840 --> 00:06:30,722
So if you have a fancy font that fits your game style,

112
00:06:31,282 --> 00:06:33,584
it's okay to do that, but it's highly recommended

113
00:06:33,624 --> 00:06:36,946
to have an option to turn that off, which I've seen more

114
00:06:36,987 --> 00:06:38,988
and more games, and that's really a great thing.

115
00:06:39,829 --> 00:06:42,531
If nobody can read your text, then again, it's sort of

116
00:06:42,551 --> 00:06:43,832
like it may as well not exist.

117
00:06:44,072 --> 00:06:46,294
So none of us are sitting down and saying,

118
00:06:46,834 --> 00:06:48,315
let's make games people can't play,

119
00:06:48,375 --> 00:06:50,116
or let's make menus people can't use.

120
00:06:50,517 --> 00:06:52,218
So it's important to keep these things in mind.

121
00:06:52,989 --> 00:06:58,073
Resize is recommended, however, that's not a pass to say you should have super tiny font to begin with.

122
00:06:58,753 --> 00:07:06,019
I do recommend having larger fonts like these minimum sizes. It's okay to make your resize go smaller.

123
00:07:06,432 --> 00:07:10,014
but just keep in mind that that shouldn't necessarily be the default.

124
00:07:10,735 --> 00:07:12,215
When it comes to subtitling,

125
00:07:12,436 --> 00:07:14,957
you do want to make sure you don't cover the entire screen.

126
00:07:15,477 --> 00:07:16,818
But at the same point in time,

127
00:07:17,158 --> 00:07:20,340
for most text, there really is no maximum size.

128
00:07:20,820 --> 00:07:23,422
If you make an okay button that fills the entire screen,

129
00:07:23,902 --> 00:07:25,663
technically speaking, that's perfectly fine.

130
00:07:27,544 --> 00:07:30,226
You're probably wondering when I'm going to get to the topic of menu narration.

131
00:07:31,123 --> 00:07:35,585
This means, menu narration means providing an audible way

132
00:07:35,725 --> 00:07:38,145
of navigating menus and game experiences.

133
00:07:38,585 --> 00:07:41,466
The primary audiences are for people who are blind,

134
00:07:41,586 --> 00:07:43,787
low vision, have cognitive issues,

135
00:07:44,127 --> 00:07:46,647
sensory processing issues, or just those

136
00:07:46,687 --> 00:07:48,288
who just in general have issues reading.

137
00:07:48,388 --> 00:07:49,468
Maybe they don't know English

138
00:07:49,708 --> 00:07:51,008
or whatever language your game is in.

139
00:07:51,729 --> 00:07:52,729
These help all those groups.

140
00:07:54,989 --> 00:07:58,090
One thing to keep in mind is that wording matters.

141
00:07:59,274 --> 00:08:09,037
Now, when you're doing menu narration, you have to describe everything that's on the screen in some useful way, particularly the areas that involve navigation.

142
00:08:10,517 --> 00:08:20,000
This includes things like specifying what the control names are, what they do, what their current setting is, and that's actually the setting current setting is actually really important.

143
00:08:20,440 --> 00:08:25,602
Let's say you're going up to a light switch in a room and that light switch controls the light in a different room.

144
00:08:26,342 --> 00:08:28,824
If you're turning it on and off, if you walk up to a switch,

145
00:08:28,884 --> 00:08:31,145
and it's just a button, and it says toggle light switch,

146
00:08:31,806 --> 00:08:32,486
is the light on?

147
00:08:32,967 --> 00:08:33,627
Is the light off?

148
00:08:34,128 --> 00:08:35,109
Are you turning the light on?

149
00:08:35,709 --> 00:08:36,430
There's no way to know.

150
00:08:37,290 --> 00:08:38,831
The same problems exist in games.

151
00:08:38,871 --> 00:08:41,073
It's important to say what the current setting is.

152
00:08:42,254 --> 00:08:44,376
But it's also okay, let's say if you have something

153
00:08:44,416 --> 00:08:47,698
like a slider, to shorten it while you're using the thing.

154
00:08:47,798 --> 00:08:49,460
So let's say you have, you say at the beginning,

155
00:08:49,820 --> 00:08:51,902
you have a slider and the current value set is 50.

156
00:08:52,682 --> 00:08:53,103
That's fine.

157
00:08:53,814 --> 00:08:55,195
Let's say you're sliding the slider.

158
00:08:55,275 --> 00:08:56,495
You don't have to say that every time.

159
00:08:56,555 --> 00:08:57,576
You can say 51, 52.

160
00:08:58,416 --> 00:09:00,557
That's perfectly acceptable.

161
00:09:01,378 --> 00:09:02,098
So keep that in mind.

162
00:09:02,698 --> 00:09:04,339
It is also important to narrate items

163
00:09:04,379 --> 00:09:07,701
that require user action that are not navigatable.

164
00:09:08,401 --> 00:09:10,502
It is recommended to make everything navigatable,

165
00:09:11,002 --> 00:09:13,404
but if that doesn't fit your needs,

166
00:09:13,564 --> 00:09:15,645
then it's okay to narrate things

167
00:09:15,845 --> 00:09:17,225
when the screen first loads.

168
00:09:18,186 --> 00:09:19,447
So, but that's still important to do.

169
00:09:20,544 --> 00:09:24,687
If you need more examples or would like more examples beyond what this presentation covers today,

170
00:09:24,707 --> 00:09:28,651
I highly recommend trying turning on Windows narrator.

171
